// Abstract class is a class that cannot be instantiated and is meant to be subclassed. It can contain abstract methods (methods without a body) that must be implemented by subclasses, as well as concrete methods (methods with a body).
// In Java, an abstract class is declared using the "abstract" keyword. It can have both abstract and concrete methods. Abstract classes are used to provide a common base for subclasses and to enforce a certain structure on the subclasses.
// wap in java to demonstrate abstract class by creating an abstract class with an abstract method and a concrete method, then create a subclass that extends the abstract class and implements the abstract method.


abstract class Vehicle{
    // Abstract method (does not have a body)
    abstract void start();
    // Concrete method (has a body)
    void fuelType(){
        System.out.println("Petrol/Diesel");
    }
}
// Subclass (Car) that extends the abstract class (Vehicle)
class Car extends Vehicle{
    // Implementing the abstract method
    void start(){
        System.out.println("Car is starting with key");
    }
}









